caption: I was  really disappointed. I thought it will be much better, but the quality of the food was not good at all. Also taste was far from the promises in menu. There are many better places around

Saturday evening visit.  Not terribly busy, so no problem getting a seat.  I had the teriyaki chicken bowl with rice, it was very good.  My companion had vegetable bowl with lo mein,. It was a little bland.  We shared ginger chicken potstickers, bbq Berkshire pork bao, and a coconut custard bao.  Aside from the vegi lo mein, the food was good.  It was ready quick and the staff was friendly enough.
I LOVE IT THE FOOD HERE

Terrible sticky vegetarian bao with overcooked vegetables which were mushy. No flavour as well. The ginger drink was okay but tasted more like lemon soda.  Also the place smelled nasty.

Personally I'm sure that many will like myself enjoy the food served here. I do however have quite a few issues. 1) good luck finding a place to sit. Even worth as few customers they had they have very limited seating. 2) Speaking of seating. If you or anyone in your group has trouble sitting in bar stools then stop now and go somewhere else, because that's all you're going to get there. 3) Low quality but gimmicky food. Thankfully I didn't have to pay for it because I'm positive that any price they had told me would have been too much in my mind for what I got. I've seen better Asian food from Panda Express. But, hey, steamed stuffed buns.... 4) I hope you're not very hungry. The portions here are small, even by the standards of finger food which it essentially is. You know what I don't really want to harp on this place, but only good for people who are really into that specialty Asian Cuisine and nothing else.
Super fast service, yummy food with portions that'll leave you satisfied. Definitely recommend take out cause it's a tight space to dine in
Disgusting. Not authentic at all.
Good soups

Wow Bao’s only good if you want a quick, fast, and easy meal, but the food isn’t that good or substantial-feeling. The only bao’s I’ve liked from here are the BBQ pork and coconut custard buns.  Recently when I came, they were out of BBQ pork (according to the Ritual app). Instead of telling me and my friend when we ordered at the counter, they just replaced them with Mongolian Beef baos. Maybe they thought we couldn’t tell but because my friend ordered one Mongolian Beef and one BBQ pork and got two of the same Mongolian beef, we knew.

WOW this place is BAD.  Ordered some bbq pork and they straight up lied to my face about the pieces of **** in the bag - turns out they were all “mongolian beef” and I know they did it on purpose because ritual had already said they were out of pork.  Btw I know they gave me “mongolian beef” not because it tasted anything like beef or any edible meat, but because they were “authentic” enough to include a few specs of green onion.

Definitely not your average American Chinese restaurant, authenticity is about 70% if that’s important to you, the rest 30% I’d give it to creativity. I like the business model, it feels like meet in the middle between authentic Chinese food and Americanized Chinese food, and also between a fast food restaurant and a sit down restaurant.  My favorite was the ginger chicken potstickers.

Good food for the price! Good variety of bao fillings and their combo meals look good too. I prefer more filling, but I understand that they have machine made baos. Love the bamboo steamers! Convenient kiosks outside for ordering and a nice space inside; clean!
Yummy & reasonable prices.

Came right before closing for some baos. I asked for the gluten free ones. They originally said they didn't have any but found some and steamed them up. They let myself and my friends stay in the store after closing as we waited for them to cook then eat them. I can't remember the cashier girl's name but she and the staff made my night by going above and beyond for me to get my first gluten free bao. I haven't had a bao in years since my Celiac disease diagnosis and it was amazing having one here. Thank you for your kindness and delicious baos. 🙏 #glutenfree
Over Rated Asian Cuisine & Overpriced

The Bao buns are delicious. The wontons in the wonton noodle soup are delicious too. The actual soup and noodles have no flavour except for sesame oil. There are no condiments to add more flavour or spice like soya sauce or hot oil.
Gest food the bone broth is too die for delicious
Nice buns
Great food!

We went right before the Art in the Dark Halloween parade, and they were understaffed. It took a long time for the food to come out. The staff was apologetic and doing the best they could. The chicken pot stickers were tasty. The bao were decent. Tried the bbq pork, teriyaki chicken, and curry. I enjoyed the house made ginger ale. The Thai iced coffee was not great.
Art in the dark parade was fun

Great dumpling bao, fast and cheap. So i like bao.. lots of different types that are fun to try. It's 4$ for two. Two is probably enough but i have four when i go.. teriyaki beef, bbq pork.. they're delicious. You can order at the kiosk outside the store entrance and skip the ordering line..
Super fun concept and tasty food.
It's great.

I got 2 bao- BBQ and Chicken Teriyaki - and the seasonal pomegranate ginger ale. As someone very familiar with bao, I had some high expectations. The BBQ pork which is what I normally get, was pretty good! They were definitely missing some five spice, was shredded instead of diced, and maybe some hoisin, but overall for a modern bao place, not bad. The chicken bao was very similar, but had some sweet peppers and was very spring onion forward. Not bad, but if you’re trying it for the first time, go for the pork. They lost a star for taking longer than necessary for getting me the wrong drink. I ordered the pomegranate ginger ale, got a regular one, and had to ask for it twice after the guy at the counter said “I’ll get it for you” and never got it. Beware, it’s not your average Schweppes, it definitely has real ginger in it and is sweetened by cane sugar or something.
Extremely Rude Customer Service from Employee Winston UpChurch! Never ordering from here again.
Fast and good food!
Love the food and service. Great for a quick lunch

I've been here twice and I love the environment and the food here!  I previously ordered: Warm wasabi house noodles, flatiron steak Miso black cod, crab avocado maki  The noodles were fantastic!  This is a pretty small place so I would recommend getting a reservation!

Another wow. Great service, who j is very welcome. The rice bowls exceeded expectations, and it is worth  trying them with multigrain  rice. Give this place a try!  The visit was great, with the manager making quite the difference at lunchtime on 6/8/2019.  The bao selection is great.

Sorry but I have had amazing Bao buns in Canada. These were a complete disappointment. The BBQ pork bun was over flavored and the teriyaki chicken bun was under flavored and bland. The dough the bun was made from made me feel heavy and unwell after. I would not recommend this chain restaurant.

The man working there asked customers if their order was eat in or take out. For eat in, he put the food on plates on a tray with cutlery.  My bao were stuck together in the paper bag. So I sat down, pried them apart, and made a plate out of the paper bag. Not good service AT ALL.

Good simple Chinese/pan-Asian food with good varieties. Vibrant simple modern decor. Sauce is a bit too salty, tailoring to the American taste. Good food, nice enough location, but overpriced for what you get, so they lose on value alone. Bao is an inherently cheap food as are dumplings, so the same food you could get in China Town for half the price is simply repackaged as trendy lunch and marked up. Again, I enjoyed the food, I just don't like paying more for the same.

This place definitely did not “wow” me. While I have only had baos a couple times, this place didn’t have the best that I’ve had. I got their chocolate bao, their matcha coconut bao, and their Kung pao chicken bowl. I’ll go ahead and say that their Kung pao chicken tasted like any standard Kung pao chicken you get at a fast food Chinese place, but I was able to at least substitute cauliflower rice for regular rice which was a nice tough. Their baos were barely filled, and the buns themselves seemed a little dry. The flavor itself was nice, having the sweet coconut flavor or gooey chocolate was a nice change of pace from usual fatty, meaty baos. So far this is a 3/5, but I will go ahead tomorrow and update the rating accordingly after trying a couple of their regular baos.

Wow Bao was a real wow, so a bow to the Wow bow. The Bao was soft, sweet and the lure of one made us try all the different ones like bbq pork, Thai curry, spicy kung pap etc. The soup was the highlight. Don't be surprised when they give it in a take away cup as against a bowl. That didn't deter the taste buds from asking for more. Definitely recommend. Go for the spicy potstickers too.

You literally place an order on a tablet, the chef prepares your food, and when they call you up to take your order you walk up to your bin, tap it, and it opens for you with your prepared food inside of it. Great place for a quick bite to eat. The Bao were delicious and they had many options to choose from. The sauce was also top notch. They can be surprisingly filling so don’t order too many if you’re just looking for a snack.

I got 2 baos, the teriyaki chicken and the pumpkin. They were both great! Just the right amount of sweetness for the pumpkin bao. Their seasonal ginger ale was solid too. Also, my order was ready really quickly. I will definitely come here to try more stuff, and since there's a lot of seating and its so close to the train stations, it's probably a good choice for lunch breaks. On the way in, I saw that you can grab baos (heat up at home) and a couple other items to-go as well

I've been here a few times so I avoid the lunch rush (11:30 am to 1 pm). This particular experience, I used the Ritual app to preorder and pay for my food and pick it up in the restaurant. At 2:15 pm, it was pretty empty, but the "order ready" notification and actual order being ready was 7 minutes off (I only have 30 min. lunch, so time is important). They do have 2 kiosk outside the doors to preorder and pay for your food (I previously used this method as the during summer, the lines get long quick). All-in-all, the food is fresh and hot, but a bit pricey if you want a variety. I still would recommend the restaurant as it does have friendly staff, good food and a great location.
Good flavors. Bad customer service.

Glad I came here, good baos and dishes. I had the orange chicken and lo mein. Really good and flavorful, I enjoyed the baos, they had plenty of meat and flavor. Good combo deal the bowl and 2 bao. Good spot for a quick Asian inspired comfort food spot.

Will not return. The veggie bowl food lacked flavor and seemed unauthentic. Do not order cauliflower instead of rice, it was under cooked. Even the hibiscus juice needed an extra boost. I did not like it. One positive, the service was quick and the atmosphere is good for waiting until your next move.
Food was excellent! Staff was a little gruff but the food more than made up for it.

OK price, small portion: $24US for 2ppl: 1 soup, 1 rice and 2 baos. My noodles are a bit cold, broth was warm, hot not; however, my bf's rice was really tasty. Bao is AWESOME! Thai tea was a bit too sweet for me. I took it back to my hotel and added more ice to dilute it. They don't offer hot sauce on side :( sorry I'm asian, needed some spicy flavour. Loved the food and delicious! Cashier was awesome and friendly as well!

We always eat a ton of Asian cuisine whenever we take a trip to Chicago-- Wow Bao is always on our list!! We ordered 8 baos (labeled by the paper on the bottom) and 8 dumplings. Use the dipping sauces! Bring some flavor to the buns!! 🎉🎉

20 min for 2 bao with both kiosks down. Better hope no one else is hungry. Won't be back.

Was looking forward to trying this place for a while and was certainly disappointed. The Bao and noodle bowl was ready while I was still paying. The bao were 75% bun, and not hot at all. “Steamed buns”, they most certainly were not, or if they were, they hadn’t seen any type of heat source anytime recently. I probably would have been happier had they zapped the buns in the microwave for 30 seconds. As I peeled off the paper, the room temperature buns stuck to the bottom wrapper. The noodle dish was literally a bowl of noodles with scoop of teriyaki chicken mixture dropped on top, granted the teriyaki mix was actually pretty tasty, but what a lack of effort. Potstickers were small and super greasy. What a joke, after $16 I was STILL hungry. Talk about small portions. I need Chinatown ASAP to remember what an actual bao tastes like. Besides the food being incredibly unfulfilling, the employees were very kind and helpful. I just wonder if this is the norm at WowBao...
Nice fast food Asian fusion place. The Bao are quite nice and substantive. Entrées are reasonably priced with generous serving sizes.
Had a soup pretty bland..

Grew up eating baos and I must admit how impressed I am by this "fast food" style approach.  I love the adapted flavors such as the thai green curry chicken and the vegetarian whole wheat edamame baos which in my opinion represents a successful fusion of a well made bao and trendy, familiar flavors catered to a broader palate.  I would reccomend for people to try other "unconventional" flavors as well as I am sure the recipes are well crafted to be tasty to most people.  It is a shame that I have only experienced Wow Bao in Chicago. I would love to see them branch out to other major cities.
